Vulnerabilities exploited usually fixed as soon as possible in the next revision of iOS by Apple. Therefore,

JailbreakMe is the easiest way to free your device. Fully customizable, themeable, and with every tweak you
could possibly imagine.

Check organizations
legal posture (security policy)
on permitted activities with corporate devices

Topic 11: Mobile forensics (IOS)
Data Structure and Artifacts
Geographical Location and Wi-Fi Data
The cellLocationLocal table contains longitude, latitude, altitude, timestamps and tower data
The wifilocation table contains longitude, latitude, MAC, and timestamps of wireless infrastructures the iOS
device has utilized
The
consolidated.db
file found in private/var/Library/Caches/locationd can hold a tremendous amount of
geolocation data
example iPhones camera will attempt to store longitude and latitude when a photo is taken
Many iOS applications will attempt to cache the users location and store GPS data depending on the
purpose of the application
GPS and Wi-Fi evidence can be a sought after item to help build a picture of the iOS device location at a
specific time and also users habits
Call History
The call history of an iOS device that can place cellular calls is contained in call_history.db
Call History in /private/var/Library/CallHistory
AddressBook
The AddressBook.sqlitedb file in the iOS can contain a wealth of information about the owners personal
contacts
AddressBook in /private/var/mobile/Library/AddressBook
Browser Cache
This particular plist file is in XML format and can be read with a text viewer
Search terms from using the Safari browser can be found in the
RecentSearches.plist
file
Browser Searches in /private/var/mobile/Library/Caches/Safari
Browser Cookies
Safari cookies can be an important piece of evidence when identifying web browsing activities from the device
Browser Cookies in /private/var/mobile/Library
Text Messages
Review text messaging communication
/private/var/mobile/Library/SMS the sms.db can be found
Notes
Review acronym or keywords that may be useful to investigation
Notes in /private/var/mobile/Library/Notes
Passwords
In some cases the passwords will be encrypted by the iOS encryption keychain procedure and will need 3rd
Party Tools to be decrypted
Accounts and passwords such as Voicemail passwords, wireless access point key phrases and device login
passcodes can be found inside this database
Contains key-chain-2.db file
iOS applications use Apples keychain for password management
Passwords in /private/var/Keychains
Keystrokes
Intent is to aid user in typing thus technical or special keywords that may not be Standard English words or
acronyms that could be helpful for the investigation
Any word entered into applications like Notes, Safari, Messages, Facebook or any application that will allow
text input, will be captured
This dictionary stores words typed by the user during the course of using the device
The dynamic dictionary is the text file dynamic-text.dat
Keystrokes in /private/var/mobile/Library/Keyboard
Photos
The first picture taken will be named IMG_0001 and will continue numbering without regards to files being
deleted or moved
The camera application numbers the images from the iOS device sequentially
Photos within the 100APPLE folder indicate that they were taken from the device itself
The pictures found here will have timestamp metadata
This folder will contain photos either taken or synced to the device
Photos in private/var/mobile/media/DCIM
iTunes Backup
The
Manifest.plist
file contains metadata about the backed up files
The IMEI number can be found here along with the phone number
The
Info.plist
file contains data that can be used to confirm the backup matches the device.
The
Status.plist
provides data about the latest backup. Consists fields:
SnapshotState:
This identifies whether the backup process has successfully finished
BackupState:
This identifies whether the backup is a new backup or one that has been updated
Date:
This is the timestamp of the last time the backup was modified
UUID:
This is the Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) of the device
IsFullBackup:
This identifies whether or not the backup was a full backup of the device
The root of the backup folder will contain the status, info and manifest plist files
Inside the backup folder there are several interesting files that will provide information on whether the
examiner is reviewing the correct iOS device
Applications
iTunesMetadata.plist from the root application folder contains information related to device, Apple
account name, date of purchase etc.
The examiner can occasionally find username and password data, cookies, or images that will help provide
evidence
Depending on the application, varying configuration files, plist files and XML data will be found.
Common files are found within most applications folders such as info.plist, resourcerules.plist and
applestores.db.
Downloaded applications from iTunes, user data are stored under /private/var/mobile/ or /User/
unique ID will be consistent across all iOS devices
assigned a 32 character alphanumeric universally unique identifier by Apple
(Example: /User/Applications/GA07A3WW- 0E39-33OJ-B947-9CAA16688G22) -UUID
This directory will hold the files associated with each application
Example: /private/var/mobile/Application or /User/Application
This includes the Address Book, Mail, Calendar, Maps, Notes, YouTube, Safari, Messages, Weather and
Voicemail applications
The default applications store their data in the private/var/mobile/Library folder
Timestamps
Timelines are an essential element for forensic analysis and in the digital world and time stamps are
recorded for many events
The iOS operating system provides MACB (modified, accessed, changed, born date) times and can be vital
when used with a timeline
An iOS device will have many Sqlite and plist files that can build a case for a forensic examiner
Other files will be stored in SQLite databases, XML files or binary format
Some files will be stored in text format and easily readable
The folder structure resembles a UNIX layout and there are several directories the examiner will immediately
be interested in
The iOS directory structure is common across all iOS devices
It is very necessary to understand how data are stored in device
Important artifacts which are generated by features of the system or interaction of the user with the device
Exif metadata
Exchangeable image file (EXIF)
Contains, Timestamps, Longitude, latitude, location and device information depending on the device used to
capture
A standard that specifies the formats for images, sounds, used by digital cameras, scanners and other
systems handling image and sound files recorded by digital cameras or voice recorders
SQL Lite Databases
Native iOS applications such as Calendar, Text Messages, Notes, Photos, Address Book utilize this database
structure to store and organize their data
It uses SQLite databases to store user data, the tool SQLite browser is used to explore and read SQL Lite
database
Logical extraction of the iPhone could provide lots of SQLite database files
SQLite data format is a popular format for mobile devices and open source applications.
Property List (Plist)
These files could be open to the simple text editor to view the contents
Contains useful artifacts related to web cookies, email accounts, GPS Map routes and searches system
configuration preferences, browsing history and bookmarks etc.
Property lists/XML files are used in the management of configuration of OS and applications
Originally Apple used the NeXSTEP format or a binary format for these files but this was deprecated and a
new XLM format was introduced
Plist is a data file (sometimes called a property file) used to store various types of data on iOS and Macintosh
operating systems.

Keychain.db, which contains user password from various applications
This partition is where all iTunes applications will reside along with the users profile data
It is Read/Write partition
This partition will be the focus of most Investigation
Contains user data
System partition
Containing only system files, upgrade files and basic applications
Read only partition
Firmware/OS partitions
IOS File System
HFS+ File system
Structure of HFS+
Last 512 Bytes are reserved
Alternate Volume Header
It is Back up Volume header located at Last 1024 byte of the volume
Startup File
Actual data is stored in the file system and tracked by the file system.
It assists the booting system which does not have built-in ROM support.
Attribute File
It contains the customizable attributes of a file
Catalog File
It organizes data using balanced tree system as mentioned previously. It utilizes to find the location of file or
folder within the volume. It also contains the metadata of file like creation and modification date, permissions.
Extent Overflow file
It consists of a pointer to the extent of the. If the file is larger than eight contiguous allocation blocks, then it
uses extents.
Allocation file
It keeps track of allocation blocks used by the file system. It basically includes a bitmap. Each bit represents
the status of the allocation block. If it is set to 1, that means Allocation block is used, and if it is 0, that means
allocation block is not used.
Volume Header
It contains information about the structure of HFS Volume. It keeps track of Catalog ID Numbering and
increases it one each time file added. HFS+ volume header also contains signature H+.
Reserved Boot Block
first 1024 bytes are reserved boot blocks
When data are added or deleted, it runs the algorithm to keep balance
Trees are consists of nodes
It uses B * tree (Balanced tree) structure to organize data
HFS files system uses catalog file system to organize data
HFS uses both absolute time (Local time) as well as UNIX time so one can identify the location of the system
UNIX time e.g. 1349896210, found in moz_cookies (firefox), global_history.dat (opera)
Absolute time e.g. 371589010, found in History.plist(safari)
There are two (2) types of Blocks in the HFS system
Allocation blocks
group of logical blocks used to track data. Allocation blocks, Can be tied together as groups to be utilized
more efficiently by HFS
Logical Blocks
which are numbered from first to last within the volume
Disk formatted with HFS has 512-byte Blocks at Physical level
Provides large data sets
Apple developed Hierarchical File System (HFS)
iOS Standard Directories: Where Files Reside
tmp/
This directory to write temporary files that do not need to persist between launches of your app
Library/
The Library Directory Stores App-Specific Files such as data files, caches, resources, preferences
Documents/Inbox
Specifically, the Mail program places email attachments associated with your app in this directory
This directory to access files that your app was asked to open by outside entities.
Documents/
This directory to store user-generated content which are Userdata
AppName.app
This directory contains the app and all of its resources

Minimum set of privileges it needs to get its job done
By enforcing a very strict set of rules on which apps can be installed on a device and exactly what they can do
Sandboxing, a technology whose primary job is security and control

iPod Touch models featured

Camera, Wi-Fi Capabilities, Safari web browser, Storage and Playback for Audio, Video and Photo, YouTube

An examiner could retrieve forensic data from storage, browser, gallery, etc. on an iPod

Jailbreaking
Implications
Apple considers jailbreaking iOS to be a violation of its terms and conditions of use and advises customers
that the practice exposes a phone to several risks, including
Shortened battery life
Potential crashes and freezes
Stability issues
Security vulnerabilities
This method is used when root access of the file system is required as well as for the physical acquisition
This method is not accepted forensically because it may overwrite some important data but it allows
performing physical acquisition efficiently
user could gain access to all partitions including file system with read-write only permissions
Jailbreaking allows the device owner to gain full access to the root of the operating system and access all the
features
Jailbreaking is the process of exploiting the flaws of a locked-down electronic device to install software other
than what the manufacturer has made available for that device
Operating modes of iOS devices
It is necessary that examiner or Investigator should be aware of this mode as this knowledge is required to
decide during the forensic acquisition that on which mode device should be operated to allow efficient
extraction of data
IOS devices can be operated in three modes
DFU (Device Firmware Upgrade) mode
During boot up, if Boot ROM is not getting a load or verify, then iPhone presents the Black screen
Used to perform IOS upgrading, and it is a low-level mode for diagnosis
Recovery mode
if during the normal boot process if any step is failed to load or verify
The device enters into recovery mode
Normal mode
These boot steps are signed to keep the integrity of the process
Normal mode boot process consists of three (3) steps:
IOS kernel
iBook
Low-Level Bootloader
In normal mode, the user could perform all regular activities
When iPhone is switched on, it boots in an operating system
Types of Acquisition
Acquisition via iTunes Backup
Backups are stored in alternate locations depending on the OS
MacOS
Users/%username%/Library/Application Support/MobileSync/Backup
Windows Vista, 7, 8, 10
%systempartition%\Users\%username%\AppData\Roaming\Apple Computer\MobileSync\Backup\
Windows XP
%systempartition%\documents and settings\%username%\Application Data\Apple
Computer\MobileSync\Backup
It should be noted that iTunes performs an automated backup during the sync process and/or when an
upgrade to the iOS is performed
Device typically connects to for updates or syncing music, movies and applications
If iOS device not available. A backup would be retrieved from the workstation (Windows or MacOS)
Cloud acquisition
Draw backs on cloud acquisition
Need the users Apple ID and password, plus the second, two factor - authentication factor (if 2FA is enabled)
Need proper authentication credentials
Messages (iMessage and SMS)
Health data
iCloud keychain
FileVault2 recovery token (FileVault is a disk encryption program in Mac Operating system)
iCloud Photos
iCloud Drive (full content, including third-party app data not available by any other means)
iCloud backups
Brute Force
offensive techniques like password cracking, patterns, pins, Rooting the device
Manual / logical
Very easily modify data on the device
Data extracted through other methods can also be verified using this
limitation is that only the files and data visible through the normal user interface
Manual Extraction of Chat messages (Screen Shots, export to external media)
No special tools or techniques are required
The examiner uses the user interface of the phone to browse and investigate
Advance Logical
Combines both Logical and File System extraction methods
Physical
A physical acquisition has the advantage of allowing deleted files and data remnants to be examined.
File system
This method of acquisition enables the examiner to gain more data than obtained via a logical acquisition
because it provides access to file system data.
Hashing
Hash values should be documented as well to maintain record of the Digital evidence
MD5 or SHA are widely used algorithms to calculate the Hash values
Hashing is the method used to prove the integrity of the evidence
Done after acquisition of device
Forensic acquisition
It can be done on site (at the scene) and can also be done off-site (in the lab)
This process is also known as Imaging
is the process of acquiring the original evidence in a forensically sound manner while maintaining the
integrity of it
Seizure and Isolation
Isolation Techniques (If device is OFF, DO NOT turn ON.)
You will have to turn on the phone if necessary, and treat is as if it was turn on and apply the Isolation
Techniques
Do a proper acquisition of the SIM
You will want to remove the SIM card
Back in the Forensic Lab
Bring it back to Forensic Lab
If you have a Faraday bag handy, place the phone along with the adapter and charger into the Faraday bag
Place it in an Evidence Bag or Box

If you have a Faraday bag handy, place the phone along with the adapter and charger into the Faraday bag

Connect the phone to a power bank
Check and manually disable, if necessary, "hotspots or any GPS locations, the Wi-Fi and Bluetooth toggles
mode (these may be left on even in Airplane mode if the user enabled Wi-Fi once in that mode)
Place the phone in airplane mode

if powered on, check battery status, network status

Topic 10: Mobile forensics (Android)
Ways to store data
Ways to store data locally in an Android app
Network
To do network operations, the classes in the java.net.* and android.net.* packages can be used
You can use the network to store and retrieve data on your own web-based services
SQLite database
<html>
<body>
The SQLite files used by the apps are generally stored at
/data/data/<ApplicationPackageName>/databases
</body>
</html>
SQLite is a popular database format present in many mobile systems
External storage
Data stored in SD Card are public and can be accessed by other applications, provided the requesting apps
have the necessary permissions
SD cards are usually formatted with the FAT32 filesystem, however it can be stored as other filesystems, such
as EXT3 and EXT4, are also being used increasingly
External storage can be a removable media, such as an SD card or non-removable storage that comes with
the phone
Files can also be stored by the apps in external storage.
Internal storage
Usually, shared pref, lib, Cache, database folders are created for most of the applications
Internal data for each of the app is stored in respective folders
Data stored here is private and cannot be accessed by other applications (unless they have root access)
These files are located typically in the applications /data/data subdirectory
Shared preferences
<html>
<body>
These files are typically stored in the application’s /data/data/<package_name>/shared_prefs
</body>
</html>
Save user preferences data of the current application (e.g user account name and passwords, settings)
Store data in key values pairs of data types in the .xml format
Various sources of Data on Android
Apps installed by the user
Apps installed by a wireless carrier
Apps installed by the manufacturer
Apps that come along with Android
Android devices store a lot of sensitive data through the use of apps
Android file hierarchy
Directories Overviews
Important sub-directories under /data or userdata
/system
Directory contains libraries, system binaries, and other system-related files The pre-installed applications
that come along with the phone are also present in this partition
Digital Camera Images (DCIM)
Within DCIM, you will find photos you have taken, videos, and thumbnails (cache) files. Photos are stored in
/DCIM/Camera
/sdcard
This is the partition that contains the data present on the SD card of the device There are some default
folders, such as android_secure, Android, DCIM, media, and so on, present in most of the mobiles
/misc
miscellaneous settings. Information about hardware settings, USB settings, and so on can be accessed from
this folder
/root
This folder can be accessed only if the device is rooted
This is the home directory for the root account
/proc
It contains files that have useful information about the processes
/mnt
This directory serves as a mount point for all the file systems, internal and external SD cards
/init
When booting the Android kernel, the init program is executed
/dev
This directory contains special device files for all the devices Defines the devices available to the applications
/data/data
The /data/data partition contains the private data of all the applications
/dalvik-cache
This folder contains several logs that might be useful during the examination, depending on the underlying
requirements
Data
This folder has significant importance from a forensic point of view as it holds valuable data
Most of the data belonging to a user, such as the contacts, SMS, dialed numbers, and so on, is stored in this
folder
This is the partition that contains the data of each application
d
This folder is used to mount the debugfs file system and to debug kernel
This is a symbolic link to /sys/kernel/debug
Cache
The cache may contain forensically relevant artifacts, such as images, browsing history, and other app data
There is also another directory in this folder called lost+found. This directory holds recovered files (if any) in
the event of filesystem corruption, such as incorrectly removing the SD card without unmounting it and so on
Wiping the cache doesnt affect your personal data, but simply deletes the existing data there
This is the directory (/cache) where Android stores frequently accessed data and app components
Acct
This is the mount point for the acct cgroup (control group) that provides for user accounting
Based on the device manufacturer and the underlying Linux version, the structure of this hierarchy may have a
few insignificant changes
If you are familiar with Unix-like systems, you will understand the file hierarchy in Android very well
A basic understanding of how Android organizes its data in files and folders helps a forensic analyst narrow
down his research to specific locations
Android File Systems
Android File Systems: Partitions
Partitions
SD-EXT or /sd-ext
It is an additional partition on SD card that act as data partition in some custom ROMs that have the features
like app2sd to get additional storage for installing their apps
This partition is commonly used by custom ROMs and not a standard Android partition.
SDCARD or /sdcard
The SD card can be internal or external SD card depending on the device
This partition is for the SD card, not for the internal memory. It is used to store any type of data such as media,
documents, ROM etc
MISC or /misc
This partition contains other important system setting information, such as a USB configuration, carrier ID,
and other hardware settings
CACHE or /cache
This partition is used to store frequently accessed data such as recovery logs and update packages
downloaded over the cellular network
DATA or /data
It contain all the user data like sms, contacts, settings and all data related to installed applications
The devices internal storage for application dat
RECOVERY or /Recovery
Recovery partition allows the device to boot into the recovery console through which activities such as phone
updates and other maintenance operations are performed
SYSTEM or /system
Without this partition, the device cannot boot into normal mode
The Android system image here contains the Android framework, libraries, system binaries, and preinstalled
applications
BOOT or /boot
It contains the kernel and RAM disk
This partition has the information and files required for the phone to boot
BOOTLOADER
Responsible for booting the Android kernel and booting into other boot modes, such as the recovery mode,
download mode, and so on
There may be other partitions which differ in each model such as sdcard, sd-ext
In the file system partitions are represented by directories
Android uses more than one file system and multiple partitions to organize files and folders in the device
Pseudo File Systems
tmpfs
Ysfs
rootfs, procfs
control group (cgroup)
For example, /proc on many operating ssytems is a process information file system which dynamically
generates directories for every process
virtual entries that the file system itself makes up on processes or functions
Media-Based File Systems
Virtual File Allocation Table (VFAT)
File Allocation Table (FAT, FAT12, FAT16 & FAT32)
EXTended file system (EXT2/EXT3/EXT4)
Flash Memory File Systems
Robust File System (RFS)
Yet Another Flash File System version 2 (YAFFS2)
Journal Flash File System version 2 (JFFS2)
Flash Friendly File System (F2FS )
Extended File Allocation Table (exFAT)
Is a type of non-volatile memory that erases data in units called blocks and rewrites data at the byte level
Common Android File Systems that are supported by Android Phones can be classified into three (3) main
categories
Pseudo File Systems
Media-Based File Systems
Flash Memory File Systems
Android is developed on Linux kernel and Linux supports many file systems
There is no singularly defined file system for Android
Android Security
Secure interposes communication
All communications between the processes using the Binder framework occur through the Linux kernel driver,
/dev/binder
The Binder framework in Android provides the capabilities required to organize all types of communication
between various processes
As discussed, sandboxing is obtained between the processes using UID assigned to different processes
Application Signing
The key store and private key which is used during signing need to be protected for pushing a new update to
the application
All android apps are signed by the developer/owner to determine the author of the app
SELinux in Android
With SELinux Android, if a user installs the malicious app, malware cannot access the OS and corrupt the
device
SE android uses MAC (Mandatory Access Control) which ensures Application runs in an isolated environment
From Android 4.3, SELinux (Security Enhanced Linux) is supported by Android
Application sandboxing
So, if an application tries to do something malicious, it can do within its context and permission it has been
assigned by the OS
By default, an application cannot access data of other application
Every android application is assigned is a UID and is run as a different process
By default, Android make use of Linux user-based protection model
User-based permissions model
We cannot install an android application with few permissions. Either we have to accept all the permissions
or decline to install it
When a user installs the application, Android presents permission list to the user so that they can view the list
to allow or disallow the installation
Applications must declare a list of permissions they require in a file called manifest.xml
Android OS has implemented permission model for individual apps
The security features and offerings that are incorporated aim to achieve three (3) things:
o To make sure that one application cannot access the data of another application
o To protect system resources
o To protect user data
Linux kernel provides Android security features
Android by default runs on Linux kernel
Android Architecture
The Application Layer
There are two kinds of apps, System apps and User Installed apps
The topmost layer in the Android stack consists of applications called apps, which are programs that users
directly interact with
Java API Framework
Java API framework allows developers to create applications using modular system components and
services as building blocks
Content Providers allows applications to access other applications data, and share their own
Activity Manager manages the lifecycle as applications, and their back stacks the order in which each
